text: there is no dedicated imaging of the neck on pacs and comparison is made to the most recent enhanced mr examination of ___.though there are a number of very small lymph nodes in the submandibular region and the anterior and posterior cervical triangles, bilaterally, none approaches ct size criteria for pathologic enlargement.however, there is a somewhat ill-defined ovoid soft tissue nodule in the right paramedian deep subcutaneous soft tissues of the mid-neck, at roughly the c4-c5 level.this measures up to 13 mm ap and demonstrate some infiltration of adjacent tissues, but no central necrosis (4:35, 7:21).there is a similar but smaller lesion located more cephalad, in the left paramedian deep subcutaneous tissues, posteriorly (4:23, 7:46); while these may simply represent sebacious cysts, other processes are not excluded.no other discrete soft tissue mass is appreciated.the aerodigestive tract is unremarkable in appearance, with no exophytic mucosal or discrete submucosal lesion.remainder of the examination is notable for relatively well-defined and low-attenuation lesion(s) in the posterior aspect of the lower pole of the right lobe of the thyroid gland measuring up to 19 mm (4:59); the gland is otherwise homogeneous in appearance.noted is lobulated mucosal thickening with near-complete opacification of the right maxillary sinus and hyperattenuating, likely inspissated contents.there is also mucosal thickening involving the anterior ethmoidal air cells.also demonstrated is multilevel, multifactorial degenerative disease involving the cervical spine.this is most marked at the c5-c6 more than c4-c5 and c6-c7 levels where there is ventral spinal canal and bilateral neural foraminal narrowing.

text: helical images were obtained through the neck without iv contrast administration.correlation is made to the prior ct of the spine from ___.there is slight increase involving the overall size of the lesion within the right parotid gland, mostly confined to the deep portion.the lesion measures 17 x 19 mm and has changed its attenuation possibly due to internal liquifaction or necrosis.differential considerations would include a pleomorphic adenoma or an intraparotid lymph node.the left parotid gland is unremarkable.the lower neck was not included on this examination.the visualized airways are patent.there is a small retention cyst within the right maxillary sinus inferiorly.

text: there has been interval decrease in the amount of fluid previously seen in the left side of the neck which was predominantly posterior to the left sternocleidomastoid muscle.there is evidence of a soft tissue defect on the left consistent with the patient's history of incision and drainage in this area.there is still some stranding in the soft tissues of the left neck perhaps slightly decreased.multiple small lymph nodes are seen throughout the neck and in a submental location, left greater than right.note is again made of lack of opacification within the left internal jugular vein.there is no evidence of osseous destruction.note is again made of a small amount of mucosal thickening within the sphenoid sinus on the left.the lung apices are clear.the relatively hypodense nodule in the left thyroid gland/isthmus is not significantly changed and appears to contain some calcification.the left sternocleidomastoid muscle continues to appear slightly more edematous compared to the right and is of slightly lower attenuation compared to the right.

text: there is nonopacification of the left vertebral artery beginning at the c7 level just prior to it entering the foramen transverserarium.the left vertebral artery is not opacified throughout its course in the foramen transversarium of the cervical spine.the vessel is reconstituted (presumably by collaterals) at the c3 level and then can be followed entering the skull and forming a normal-appearing basilar artery.the vertebral artery has a normal-appearing origin from the left subclavian artery.the left common carotid, internal carotid and external carotid arteries appear normal.the right common carotid, internal carotid, external carotid, and vertebral arteries are normal.there is no active extravasation within the neck.there are prominent collateral vessels in the posterior soft tissues of the left neck.some of these are arteries contributing to the reconstitution of the left vertebral artery, and others connect with the venous system.there are bilateral small lymph nodes in the neck, which do not individually meet size criteria for pathologic enlargement.additionally, there are a few small lymph nodes in the ap window within the chest.there is a mild amount of prevertebral soft tissue swelling.there is high attenuation within the soft tissues posterior to the right neck at the c5/6 level consistent with a hematoma.there is no active extravasation.there is a small amount of layering fluid within the sphenoid sinus.there is ground-glass opacity seen in both lung apices, as well as background emphysematous changes.the lungs are incompletely imaged.please see the dedicated chest ct report of this region.the patient is intubated and has a ng tube in place.

text: contrast injection was performed from the left upper extremity.a left-sided dialysis catheter is identified from the left subclavian vein with tip terminating into the right atrium.a 20-mm short segment occlusion of the left subclavian vein is identified, located approximately 5 mm from the insertion point of the dialysis catheter into the left subclavian vein.there are extensive collateral veins in the left upper chest wall which reconstitute the flow in the distal left brachiocephalic vein.the svc is widely patent.there is no opacification of the right brachiocephalic vein in this arterial phase study.the aorta, great vessels and pulmonary arteries appear unremarkable.coronary artery calcifications are present.minimal pericardial effusion.mild cardiomegaly.bilateral small-to-moderate pleural effusion with atelectasis of the adjacent lung.limited images of the upper abdominal organs are unremarkable.

text: the right vertebral artery shows only minimal string-like filling within 1 inch of its origin from the right subclavian artery.distal to that, there is complete occlusion of the right vertebral artery including the v1, v2, and v3 segments.there is some minimal retrograde filling of the intracranial (v4) segment of the vertebral artery.this occlusion is likely related to a lateral process fracture of c2 extending into the foramen transversarium causing vascular injury to the right vertebral artery, possibly dissection.the left vertebral artery, as well as the carotids bilaterally show no evidence of hemodynamically significant stenosis, occlusion, dissection, or aneurysm.the proximal left internal carotid artery measures 4.8 mm, the distal left ica measures 4.0 mm.the proximal right ica measures 6.1 mm, the distal right ica measures 4 mm.the basilar artery is well opacified and from the left vertebral artery.there is no evidence of masses or enlarged lymph nodes in the neck.there is bullous emphysema at the lung apices bilaterally.

text: the patient is noted to have an endotracheal tube with tip above the carina.a nasogastric tube can be seen coursing through the esophagus.within the retropharyngeal space, there is a complex amount of material likely representing combination of fluid versus hemorrhage.local infection cannot be completely excluded, based upon imaging characteristics.the expanded polytetrafluoroethylene graft can be seen coursing posterior and inferior to the retropharyngeal space fluid, but likely within this fascial compartment.the upper portion of a descending thoracic aortic graft is visualized.no significant cervical lymphadenopathy is identified.there is minimal dependent atelectasis on the lung windows.there may be a small left apical medially-located bleb.evaluation of the neck via the bone windows reveals no fractures or abnormal lytic/blastic lesions.

text: a large fluid-density process spans the midline in the retropharyngeal/prevertebral soft tissue space.this is indistinctly marginated and extends caudad to the level of the hyoid.cephalad, hypodensity reaches the level of the lower nasopharynx.this hypodense material also extends laterally, and appears trans-spatial, involving the carotid spaces, right more than left, to surround the jugular veins, which appear patent by opacification, bilaterally.anteriorly, there is notable involvement of the uvula, which is markedly enlarged, as well as the lingual and palatine tonsils and epiglottis (most evident on sagittal reformations).no distinct hyperenhancing rim or margin encapsulates this hypodensity.there is noteworthy narrowing of the caliber of the oro- and hypopharynx.scattered lymph nodes are present bilaterally, none of which appear significantly enlarged by ct criteria.regional vascular structures opacify normally.limited visualization of intracranial contents and of the lung apices are both unremarkable.included osseous structures are notable for cervical spinal degenerative change, but are otherwise unremarkable, without destruction.
summary: extensive, but ill-defined edema, centered at the retropharyngeal space but extending, particularly laterally, as a trans-spatial process.there is no discrete rim- enhancing component.overall, the primary consideration is extensive phlegmon, likely related to infection.note that the absence of defined margin does not exclude the possibility of abscess.given the mass-effect of these findings, clinical correlation is recommended to assess for potential need for airway protection.

text: the proximal left vertebral artery is tortuous.otherwise, the vertebral and carotid arteries are patent throughout their cervical courses, without a hemodynamically significant stenosis.the distal right internal carotid artery measures 5.6 mm in diameter.the distal left internal carotid artery measures 5.5 mm in diameter.the patient has an endotracheal tube and orogastric tube in place.the endotracheal tube terminates 2.7 cm above the carina.there is atelectasis in the imaged upper lungs, right greater than left.

text: the lung apices are clear.there is a right subclavian central venous catheter noted.the great vessels of the neck are unremarkable.there are multiple small cervical lymph nodes, but no pathologically enlarged lymph nodes.slightly prominent bilateral jugulodigastric lymph nodes, the larger one on the right measuring 9 x 13 mm in axial dimension are probably normal.again, noted is thickening of the prevertebral soft tissues, without a discrete abscess identified, as well as thickening of the parapharyngeal tissues.the overall appearance is unchanged.the major salivary glands are within normal limits.
summary: persistent thickening of the prevertebral and parapharyngeal soft tissues, for which correlation with clinical exam is suggested, as further details are difficult to discern by ct.no discrete fluid collection, however.
